				\begin{document}$$\frac{{\mathrm {d}}}{{\mathrm {d}}t} I$$\end{document}ddtI) is another metric used to dictate policy in states such as New York and California, which could be considered. Percentage positive tests, measured as the proportion of the population infected (|I|/N), is another factor in states such as North Carolina and Georgia used to indicate the extent of disease spread.
Instead of gradual/proportional restrictions, isolated populations such as those of New Zealand, implemented strict lockdowns within the first cases with the goal of eradicating the disease before any possibility of herd immunity. Stricter policy can be modelled by increasing the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
